### Events in C#

Events enable a class to notify other classes when something of interest occurs. Events are based on delegates.

### Declaring Events

```csharp
public class Button
{
    // Event declaration using EventHandler
    public event EventHandler? Clicked;

    // Event with custom delegate
    public event EventHandler<KeyEventArgs>? KeyPressed;

    protected virtual void OnClicked()
    {
        Clicked?.Invoke(this, EventArgs.Empty);
    }
}
```

### Subscribing to Events

```csharp
Button button = new Button();

// Subscribe with method
button.Clicked += Button_Clicked;

// Subscribe with lambda
button.Clicked += (sender, e) => Console.WriteLine("Button clicked!");

// Unsubscribe
button.Clicked -= Button_Clicked;

static void Button_Clicked(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Button was clicked");
}
```

### Standard Event Pattern

```csharp
// Custom EventArgs
public class TemperatureChangedEventArgs : EventArgs
{
    public double OldTemperature { get; }
    public double NewTemperature { get; }

    public TemperatureChangedEventArgs(double old, double newTemp)
    {
        OldTemperature = old;
        NewTemperature = newTemp;
    }
}

// Publisher class
public class Thermostat
{
    private double temperature;

    public event EventHandler<TemperatureChangedEventArgs>? TemperatureChanged;

    public double Temperature
    {
        get => temperature;
        set
        {
            if (temperature != value)
            {
                double old = temperature;
                temperature = value;
                OnTemperatureChanged(old, value);
            }
        }
    }

    protected virtual void OnTemperatureChanged(double old, double newTemp)
    {
        TemperatureChanged?.Invoke(this,
            new TemperatureChangedEventArgs(old, newTemp));
    }
}

// Subscriber
public class Display
{
    public Display(Thermostat t)
    {
        t.TemperatureChanged += OnTemperatureChanged;
    }

    private void OnTemperatureChanged(object? sender, TemperatureChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Temperature changed from {e.OldTemperature} to {e.NewTemperature}");
    }
}
```

### Event vs Delegate

| Aspect | Event | Delegate |
|--------|-------|----------|
| Access | += and -= only | Can be invoked directly |
| Invocation | Only from declaring class | Anywhere visible |
| Interfaces | Can be declared in interface | Can be declared in interface |
| Protection | Protected from external assignment | Can be assigned (=) externally |

### Event Best Practices

| Practice | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| Use EventHandler<T> | Standard pattern for events |
| Null-check with ? | `EventName?.Invoke(...)` |
| Virtual OnEvent method | `protected virtual void OnEvent(EventArgs e)` |
| Custom EventArgs | Derive from EventArgs for custom data |
| Unsubscribe | Always unsubscribe to prevent memory leaks |

### Static Events

```csharp
public static event EventHandler? AppShuttingDown;
```

### Event Accessor (add/remove)

```csharp
private EventHandler? _clicked;

public event EventHandler Clicked
{
    add
    {
        _clicked += value;
        Console.WriteLine("Subscriber added");
    }
    remove
    {
        _clicked -= value;
        Console.WriteLine("Subscriber removed");
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Events follow the observer pattern. The publisher declares the event and raises it. Subscribers attach handlers using `+=`. Use `EventHandler<TEventArgs>` for the standard pattern. Always null-check events before invoking. Unsubscribe from events to avoid memory leaks.

### Common .NET Events

```csharp
button.Click          // WinForms/ASP.NET
element.Click         // WPF
PropertyChanged       // INotifyPropertyChanged
CollectionChanged     // ObservableCollection
```

